2 Ways to Commit Code

---

1st Method: Clone an Existing GitHub Repository

1. Set Up a GitHub Account  
   - Visit: https://github.com/  
   - Click "Sign up" and enter your username, email, and password.  
   - Verify your email address.  
   - Log in to your GitHub account.

2. Create Your First GitHub Repository  
   - Click "New" to create a new repository.  
   - Enter the repository name, select "Private" or "Public," and click "Create repository."

3. Clone the Repository and Commit Changes  
   - Open Command Prompt or Git Bash and run:  
     git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git  
     cd repositoryname  
   - Modify files as needed.  
   - Check the status:  
     git status -s  
   - Stage the changes:  
     git add .  
     git status -s  
   - Commit the changes:  
     git commit -a -m "Added files"  
   - Push the changes:  
     git push -u origin master  

---

2nd Method: Connect Your Local Project to GitHub

1. Create a New Local Project  
   - Open Command Prompt or Terminal in your desired directory.  
   - Run the following commands:  
     mkdir my_project  
     cd my_project  
     git init  
   - Create files (e.g., A.txt, B.txt).  

2. Stage and Commit Changes  
   - Check the status:  
     git status -s  
   - Stage the changes:  
     git add .  
     git status -s  
   - Commit the changes:  
     git commit -a -m "Added files"  

3. Connect to GitHub and Push  
   - Add the remote repository:  
     git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/repo-name.git  
   - Push the changes:  
     git push -u origin master  

---

Step 7: Verify Your Code on GitHub

1. Go to your repository on GitHub.  
2. Your files should now appear in the repository.  

---
